e Caricatures seem a bit lifeless. Also not having the faction figureheads stating what's going on really lets the game down.It also is quite tough on the hardware, I would suggest using a beefy computer. But this could just be the early stages of the game.On the brightside, It's pretty I guess. And Trading is a nice touch. But not much else has changed and had only really taken a step backwards.I think Haemimont and Kalypso really need to get their act together, After that tremendous flop that was Omerta and now This. I don't understand why I thought this may have been better.4ish/10 - Buy when it's cheap."
76561197991260217,Recommended,245620,28041640,"Posted: 29 November, 2016",all,Gionder,"I played Tropico 1, 2, 3, 4 and now the newest one. Let me give you some history for basing my opinion.Tropico 1 was fun, innovative for its time, great ambience, nice enough music (a bit repetitive) and the missions were very straight foward, like a game in that era should be.Tropico 2 was more of the same but with some great additions. The pirates theme, i guess, worked out really well. I enjoyed it for a long time before it got sort of pointless.Tropico 3 is the first installment that you can call ""the current generation"" of the Tropico games. The controls and the GUI were terrible compared to T5, but in some ways, it was more rewarding to try and accomplish the side missions.Tropico 4 was a massive improvement over T3. The best music so far, with a varied selection and you can't really get bored with them. The missions were OK, mostly made sense, which is good. Progression was very linear, in a satisfactory kind of way.Now, TROPICO 5: the music has been toned down a little. No such quality or variety as found in the fourth game.The missions are basically life-savers that pop up in just the right time or a simple do-and-get-rewarded sort of scheme. The rewards are usually immigrants, cash or good standing with other nations.The graphics have improved a bit, yes, but it's not like you'll be playing this at the closest possible zoom all the time. Granted, when you do zoom in, the textures don't look washed out too badly and the characters and objects are a little bit higher poly than in T3 and 4.The game is no longer THAT linear. You do end up being thrown back into the past to take revenge on your present-time enemies by sabotaging their past. That surprised me a bit and i liked it.The whole technology progression thing deserves a compliment. This works in much the same way as Endless Space, which, in my view, is the very best technology tree found in a strategy game. It simply works nicely and gives you a good idea of the passage of time.Overall, i would say this is, indeed, more of the same good old tropico, but it cannot be denied that it has been improved substantially. It does feel ""new"".I give it a 8.5 out of 10. You really should try it if you like city builders in the likes of Patrician and Port Royale."
