,Not Recommended,245620,32780230,Posted: 25 June,all,Foosball,"Another addition to the Tropico series. I own every single Tropico game out there and so I'm acquainted with the game. People may disagree with this review yet in comparison of the other Tropico games I don't really feel this game adds a whole lot. While Tropico 5 ushers in new options, the metrics the game offers you by way of info for economics is sorely lacking. Overall, this game takes a more casual approach towards the series with a campaign that is poorly written. For those who prefer growing your economy, enjoying a mixed economy while trying to appease facitons, perhaps stick with Tropico 4 because the constant barrage of crises faced when playing Tropico 5 turned me off.Pros:-Tropico 5 ushers in new options and concepts not found in the previous series. Things like buildings auto-demolishing themselves once they've outlived their usefulness (like a logging mill) is a welcome change to manage buildings.-The addition of newer buildings adds greater variety to the landscape.- The introduction of research points generated from a library is interesting and allows you to research a variety of upgrades.- You can upgrade certain buildings in order to enhance certain aspects like productivity of the buildngs.- You can establish trade routes now through the docks.- You can now hire managers with speficic traits to run specific buildings with those traits benefiting the buildings.- New buildings offered (i.e. Inquisition) offer the chance for you to carry out additional activities like label people heretics, etc.Cons:- The campaign is frankly confusing and poorly laid out. With the introduction of a dynasty whereby you can choose to create different members of your ruling family, it makes for too many choices in what should otherwise a simply process of going from one campaign to the next. I would have much preferred a more simple layout to show progress with the campaign.- Second, after having purchased and fought for your independence, you find yourself governing another island and yet the same Crown representative is bugging you with requests and you have to work again towards independence. The campaign should progress with different goals which makes this tedious.- There is no fluidity from one campaign to the next. Once you finish one objective, you've back in the main menu, whereby you save, and then choose another island. Why not simply transition right away?- The Crown constantly asking you for money to leave you alone is annoying and takes place way too early in the game. It takes away from growing your economy and instead you're left dishing out money left right and centre. I get that the devs wanted to make the game more challenging but frankly there are so many frequent interruptions it becomes annoying.- The Crown will let you know that your colony is doing poorly compared to other colonies and so what does it do? It penalizes you with a tax of 10k that allows you to continue playing but puts you further into debt. DUH. Penalize me for doing badly by putting me further into the hole?- In certain missions, the crown will penalize you for doing poorly but then 5 minutes send you 6k. Wtf?- In another campaign the crown will hit you with a real estate tax and then two seconds later you'll get a disbursement of 6k.- The almanac does a♥♥♥♥♥♥poor job of expanding on important aspects of your government. You cannot expand bullets under the Trade option with Economy to expand your revenue and expenses. Hell, even in Tropico 3, the GUI for info about the island was boring but it still allowed you greater freedom in clicking on certain metrics and being able to see immediately where you were hurting.- Unlike Tropico 4, setting wages for jobs is confusing. Instead of a ""wages"" option you have a budget set for the building. Budget for what? Maintenance or wages?Conclusion: Tropico 5 offers a variety of improvements in certain areas and upgrades in its buildings but for Tropico aficionados like myself, I found the game hampered by a poorly written and confusing campaign that make playing the game. It's clear that the game takes on greater economic challenges that make please some people. There is fun to be had while you play a campaign and it is clear that the devs have modernized the series but frankly I feel the game is hamstrung by the campaign. If you are a hardcore fan you may be disappointed and choose instead to stick to Tropico 4, but if this on sale it may be worth it.Oh, and one more thing: by the way, Haemimont Games: if I buy a digital game, I don't expect to have to register an account with you to download ""updates"" and get passed your stupid ♥♥♥♥ing nag screen. It is ♥♥♥♥ing annoying and completely useless. Get rid of the ♥♥♥♥ing piece of♥♥♥♥♥♥nag screen."
