76561198205539128,Recommended,245620,33005212,Posted: 29 June,all,lorger02,One of my all time favorites.  Lots of replay time on this one.
76561198049568708,Not Recommended,245620,33029494,Posted: 30 June,all,Rad Shiba,"To say Tropico 5 isn't worth picking up isn't to say it's a bad game. On the contrary, I've had quite a good deal of fun with the game, I've put 20+ hours into it in the last week or so and have had a decent amount of fun for almost all of it. However, a game needs to be reviewed in context. Many take the approach of wanting to appreciate a game in a vacuum, to take the game itself and judge it on its own merits. I don't necessarily think this way of thinking is *wrong*, but I don't think it is correct either, and it's not the way that I want to approach this game. Rather, I would like to take the approach of a die-hard, disapointed, Tropico fan. I take this approach for a few reasons. Firstly, to judge a game on its own merits, it needs to exist on its own merits. Tropico 5 does not do that, it instead builds on a decades old franchise and comes from an experienced studio. That studio's past experience should be taken into account when judging what they've accomplished. A game's merits can not exist in a vacuum, and should not be judged as such. Secondly, this review primarily serves as a buyer's guide. Tropico needs to be judged in comparison to its competition. This is how all reviews work, as comparison forms the basis for our understanding of quality, and reviews tend to score in relation to other products. As such, I would like to approach this game, as mentioned before, as a Tropico fan, and approach it in as full a context as I can.The biggest critique I can raise against Tropico 5 is that, instead of feeling streamlined, it feels like content has been cut. Streamlining isn't necessarily a bad thing. Excess fat can exist in games, trimming it isn't at all bad and quite often is an improvement. The extended cuts of movies rarely are as good as the finished, ""official"" cut because what was cut is often boring and tedious. However, streamlining is only appreciated when what it cuts is truly needless or cumbersome. Sadly, what Tropico 5 cuts from 3 (the cutting may have begun in 4, 5 might even represent compilation over 4 for all I know, but it is cut in comparison to 3, the basis of my critique so) isn't at all needless. In fact, it's what I liked the most.Tropico 5 cuts from micromanagement, which *sounds* like a good thing, but the result is that the player is disconnected, distant from their citizens. I never once felt particularly motivated to help my citizens out of empathy or desire to help, nor do I feel any joy when oppressing them for the fun of it. The people never amount to more than a number in the almanac. Tropico 3, on the other hand, gave very personal descriptions of each citizen's thoughts, one could easily bring the camera down onto one citizen and just watch their life. A detailed political background gives insight to how a citizen thinks, their thoughts clearly line up and reflect these views. One can easily and visibly see the material basis on which these views have been founded. A citizen isn't a citizen, they're a number. A person dislikes their house? You won't know except for the aggregate number in the almanac. This isn't to say that you can't figure out what a person thinks, you can, but it feels hollow. I never feel motivated to go beyond the almanac, even if the information exists. It's the difference between de facto and de jure. Yes, de jure, the information is there. It's in the game technically. But, de facto, it's not, because it doesn't matter. For a political equivalent, it's the difference between censorship in the USSR and lack of funding in the US. The USSR certainly appears more restrictive of its media, but in actuality the differences aren't terribly relevant. The degree to which this is true even prompted George Lucas to say he would have rather created Star Wars in the USSR, because there would have been less restrictions. This is the power of de facto vs de jure. Yes, citizen ""character"" is in the game, but every citizen lacks personality.The game makes some advancements on the diplomacy and military fronts, however, these end up backfiring on the game as well. Tropico 3's military system was ""buy guard towers, buy army bases, don't worry about it"". Tropico 5 makes one keep placement and funding in mind, but combat is dry as a bone. Soldiers take minutes to die even in firefights and the player lacks any control. Yes, further involvement is there in comparison to 3, but it's nowhere near enough. In 3 it was a flaw, but it was so nonexistent that I could just forget it and overlook it. In 5, it's present enough to remind me that I wish it was better. International diplomacy is similar. In 3, all one needed to worry about was not getting invaded and, if one wanted to, send some diplomatic missions to the USSR or the US and receive free stuff after a few months. Again, far from the focus. A flaw, yes, but one easily forgotten. 5 makes foreign policy missions constant, but they still amount to little more than ""avoid being invaded"". It's hollow and terribly boring.Not the result of streamlining, but econ management is absolutely horrendous in this game. I don't, and never will, expect to play a game and expect an accurate representation of how an economy would function. There are far too many variables, and the game would always reflect the ideology of the creators. A fan of Mises will create a different game economy than a fan of Krugman would who would create a different game than a fan of Anwar Shaikh would. While I would love to exercise my Paul ♥♥♥♥♥hott inspired techno-socialist ideology in a game, it isn't going to happen. However, that doesn't mean I can't enjoy being the all powerful dictator, controlling every aspect of the economy. Unrealistic as it may be, that's not what I play games for. One thing I do come to games for is entertainment, and Tropico 5 makes sure that I find that task a harder one to complete than is needed. Fundamentally, the economy is hard to manage in Tropico 5. Not from a gameplay standpoint, I've basically got the game figured out. No, it is hard because information is hard to actually find. Say, for example, you run out of coal. You won't know until you finally start looking around for reasons why your island is without power. Information is never relayed to the player effectively.I have more to say on the matter, and will upload a full review to my blog [Link here when it is uploaded], but the gist is simply this: Tropico 5 is inferior to 3. That's all there is to it, really. Just buy 3. You won't regret your choice"
