,Recommended,245620,11448834,"Posted: 28 July, 2014",all,Benjamin the Rogue,"So, Tropico 5. We meet at last. Do you know why you were brought here, Tropico #5? Because El Presidente believes with the right sort of, let's say, motivation, you could become so much more useful as a citizen of our great virtual island. But as it is right now? I don't know, Tropico 5. I don't know. Considering the work of the four previous Tropicos who have come through town, who have very rarely made any significant changes to the status quo, which I have to admit, around here we can appreciate that sort of slow gradual change considering how everything has been working just fine, you decided you wanted to make a few more, shall we say, radical changes. This has El Presidente very concerned. Let's go over the dossier, shall we?Let's start with what you've been doing around town that's got so many fellow citizens vocally supporting you. One of the biggest changes you've made is to the infrastructure. It's nice to see that you've scaled down the size of the parking garages to something manageable, and look, in the Modern area you've introduced the Metro to our tiny island! Letting citizens get from one point of the island to the other nearly instantaneously is quite the feet. Something that El Presidente truly appreciates when he wants to get out to the llama farms for some quiet and relaxation without having to drive through all of that horrible traffic. Which is another issue we see significantly less of. It is good to see more people walking instead of filling the streets with cars! I applaud you, Tropico 5, for finally resolving that issue.That reminds me, the whole Era thing. It is, if of a somewhat debatable quality, nice to have Eras from which to transition. Going from the Colonial Era to the World War Era is probably the largest change of the four. The other two are the Cold War and the Modern Era. Having the ability to upgrade certain residential units to other certain residential units is nice as the era transitions, and new constructions become available.Having Edicts become available as the Era progresses is another thing to look forward to, until finally you have access to all of them. And the Constitution! Who would have expected something like that to be introduced into our tiny island? The discovery of science, which is used to enhance the Constitution and advance the Eras, was nice as we can finally figure out that whole sliced bread thing.The price of docks is considerable cheaper than they were previously, which allows El Presidente to build many, many docks to help speed up the export of his new delicious cheese. And speaking of money, it's nice to finally be able to have a use for El Presidente's, shall we say 'private' income. Being able to use the Swiss Bank account balance level up El Presidente and his family members abilities is quite good at encouraging you to play multiple maps with the same family so you realize their full power! Oh yes, and El Presidente would like me to pass along his thanks in allowing multiple members of the family to share power on our island.For the workforce, being able to hire managers with minor Presidente-like powers to manage buildings is a nice touch indeed. The people of our island enjoy being empowered in such a way that makes them more useful to El Presidente.But now onto some concerning trends that I am seeing here. The buildings snap to a rather large grid system that while nice when fitting buildings together sometimes, is terrible unimaginative and can leave a lot of extra space between buildings where they meet at odd angles. It doesn't help any that you have taken away El Presidente's favorite toys. No longer can we build statues to honor El Presidente's might. No, now parks and decorations only come in two units, small and large. The small is one grid or two, while the large fluctuates slightly more, starting at a 4x4, and going to such sizes as 4x6, to the mighty 5x5 and 5x6. But what happened to the gardeners, Tropico 5? Did you murder them in the study with a lead pipe? Because we can no longer plant individual trees, or benches, or any of the small single items. This is a great disappointment to El Presidente, for he had quite the green-thumb.Housing has now turned into something of a mess, since, as we said, Tropicans walk far more than they did last time. Now if a Tropican can not find a house near where they live, they will opt to just build a shack near their work-site, even if there is ample housing on the island. I have been told by many who do this, Tropico #5, that they were encouraged to ignore El Presidente's benevolence and build these eyesores around the city by you.And another thing. Why have you taken away the ability of El Presidente to personally manage the wages of our citizens? Not only that, but he can no longer set prices for buildings or services. Everything has instead been rolled up into one ""budget"" function. Tropico 5, I'm concerned about this power grab. These are function that should be left up to El Presidente himself to manage, not some overly simplified ""budget bar"" that controls everything. This has actually made it HARDER to manage the economy, since if we want to pay people less, we now have to also decrease the efficiency of a building by lowering the budget. This is a big problem, and I suspect it may be sabotage!I was also shocked to discover that we need to discover our own island now! When we start administering our great government in the Colonial Era, our island is shrouded in mist, and must be explored by our soldiers during ""expeditions"" that cost a thousand dollars an event! And you can't even control them, you just click on a way point and hope they go the right route in getting there to discover it. Though the discovery of the Compass does negate this, it is none-the-less irksome.And speaking of discovery, why are our people no longer able to improve their skills concerning their profession? Why have you taken this source of pride from our people, Tropico #5? The people are also kept more out of sight as well, as no longer is El Presidente able to see them when they utilize a building. Gone are the queues that show up when you click on a service building. Instead, they are reduced to mere numbers.Having to mine minerals out of very specific ""mines"" instead of just having to dig it out of the ground did not actually turn out to be helpful. These ""mines"" take up permanent space on the map, even after they are used up and collapse. Which is another issue! When a resource node, with the exception of the fishing wharf, is used up, it is automatically destroyed, regardless of whether or not the output storage is full! This destruction of El Presidente's property at the hands of no other than you, Tropico 5, is a great crime! It is most irritating and wasteful. If a facility no longer has resources to mine, El Presidente will choose when and how it is removed, not you!And with the Edicts, while we do have some nice new interesting ones, I see the Pope is no longer able to visit our island, Tropic 5. That is a little disappointing.Elections are now quite a bit more boring. Why do you not allow El Presidente to do speeches anymore, Tropico #5? In fact, why is it that El Presidente, and the family, are not able to directly control their actions on the map? Gone are the day when El Presidente could walk up to a construction site and encourage the workers to construct faster, or walk into a service building an inspire greater service. This is very disappointing that you have talked otherwise upright citizens into ignoring El Presidente in such a way.In the end, I find my appreciation for you mixed, Tropico 5. I can stay with Tropico 4 and not really miss much, I think, but I do still enjoy your presence, even if I think you're a half step back in progress."
76561198022701030,Recommended,245620,11783075,"Posted: 19 August, 2014",all,What is a man?,best Tropico game yet 7/10
,Recommended,245620,31667097,Posted: 10 May,all,KingWeir,"Having now finished the main campaign (and one of the DLCs and half way through the 2nd DLC), I'll now consider this game finished, even though a game like this, its also very sandbox focus and in that regard, its never really finishable.But anyway, having never played any of the previous Tropico games, I finally got around to jumping on board with the fifth instalment, so I can't compare do any previous games (though I have read from other reviews that maybe the fourth instalment is better).But my review for this game, focused mainly on the campaign is actually pretty positive.It starts off with you in charge of a colony island, where the overall goal is to gain independence from the crown, and then progress from different eras up to the present (think they are, Colony, World at War, Cold War and Modern Times).In the campaign you have an...... interesting story, that progress you through these eras, while giving you objectives that make it feel like the goal isn’t necessarily just to speed through the time periods and as such works quite nicely, introducing the game mechanics, basically like one long tutorial but without the hand holding, your just told do this or build this and its up to you, how and where, so works brilliantly for newcomers like myself.A neat little tactic that I liked to try, was holding off declaring my independence from the crown as long as possible to keep receiving money from the crown and avoid suffering rebel attacks, while I try and create an self sustaining island, that would hopefully keep the locals happy once we are an independent nation.There is an occasional difficultly surge that threw me a curve ball, such as when you've got to research a specific technology within so many months, so I have built one of each research building and just ignored it while I concentrated on building my island to then only realised that I'm running out of time and I'm spamming research buildings as fast as I afford and build them to try and finish the goal. Which made me realise one nag with the game, you quite easily get lost in what you doing and then suddenly it goes wrong and you realise your last save was from ages ago, it does have an auto save but I would like it save more often.Anyway, I've ranted on long enough now, so if you like your city builders with a bit of, maybe humour is the wrong word but doesn’t take itself too seriously, while still providing an enjoyably challenge……. then you've probably already played if not this game then another Tropic game already.Oh, one thing that I did really like was, that your Islands save from campaign mission to campaign mission, as often with this sort of game, you have to build from scratch each time you start a new mission. With this your in charge of two Islands that you switch between but each one saves where you left off with that Island, so you don’t get sick of building from the ground up, while also making you think about the long term design of the Island. I literally restarted the campaign a couple of times until I got the hang of the game, as when I would return to an Island having learnt some new mechanics of the game, I was like, no, no, no, this won't do. One time I demolished all my island buildings, actually starting from scratch because of what I had learnt and how I was now leaning towards designs my Islands."
,Recommended,245620,11380194,"Posted: 23 July, 2014",all,Risetto,"Very fun game, the movement of the map is slightly annoying, but other wise a great game. You can actually lose this game if you mess up, but there are continueous saves so if you mess up and want to continue you can go back to previous saves. It has cool political aspects and many different paths on how to run your community."
,Recommended,245620,10434581,"Posted: 11 June, 2014",all,allos autos,"First, a brief history lesson. I was an avid player of Tropico 3, and snatched Tropico 4 up on the first day. I was underwhelmed, as the game seemed more to be Tropico 3.75 than a new game in its own right; for example, all of the UI and art elements were exactly the same. However, over the next several years, patches and DLC helped make Tropico 4 a truly outstanding game, far surpassing its predecessor.Now we're met with Tropico 5, and history seems to be repeating itself. Tropico 5 has a rock-solid foundation. The mechanics and the underlying systems have been streamlined and now make a lot more sense. Building variety has been diminished, but gone are a lot of buildings that you only ever used once (and that was just to find out what it did). What's left has a time and a place, and the only time you won't use a building is if it doesn't suit your playstyle (as opposed to, say, satellite dishes from Tropico 4, which had very little extra-campaign utility). I've yet to experience a crash. The new systems function well. I especially like the introduction of eras. The dynasty system works, I think. I'm not sure. I seem to get all of the bonuses all of the time, regardless of who is Presidente.That said, the game needs work. Some categories (entertainment) are far too sparse, unless you want a dozen cabarets on your island. I've experienced one game-breaking bug: I don't win Sandbox missions despite meeting the victory conditions. Hopefully that gets patched soon. Upgrading buildings is tedious, although I'm happy that they streamlined modernizing them. A big letdown is that the trademark Tropico humour largely falls flat this time around. Instead of the caricatures of various tropes (the drunken priest, the inept second-in-command) and the banter on the radio which could be genuinely funny (I still laugh at General Rodriguez's description of the Museum of Modern Art), you get ""Brokeback Mountain"" references, predictable flat-out stupidity from Penultimo, and...Lulu. One cannot be told what Lulu is, one must experience her awfulness for oneself.All told, it's a solid game that will likely only get better as time goes on. It's worth the price--you can easily get 30-40 hours of gameplay in its current state. It's still one of the best city-builder franchises out there."
