,Recommended,245620,12951412,"Posted: 15 November, 2014",all,Jakhara,"One of the crtiticisms levelled at Tropico 4 was that it was purely an extension of Tropico 3; not so much a new game as an expansion pack.In a way, the same can be said for this new offering albeit with a different engine and management focus.Running through the campaign means juggling between two islands; once you complete a scenario, you either continue on your current island or switch to the second. They have the same buildings and workforce, just the scenario parameters change.  This can be quite annoying if you've spent so long playing on one island as switching means remembering where you were up to, particularly with the new management system.Gone is the focus control of El Presidente, running him around the map to help with building times and increasing productivity; instead we get an increasing number of managers with different abilities who you have to allocate to buildings.  This can be very micro-managing, especially with your `family` who you have to send abroad on tasks and then re-allocate to a building.The scenario tasks remain pretty standard compared to previous Tropicos.  Exports/imports, tourism and rebels are still present as are the natural disasters.  A nice design touch is being able to rebuild all your destroyed building post disaster rather than finding individual ruins.Overall, there are some nice improvements and the graphics engine is certainly an improvement.  This is still a Tropico game though, and not wholly different to its predecessors.  Recommended to previous El Presidente's but if you're new to the series, you would be better off starting with Tropico 4 and the Modern Times expansion."
