,Not Recommended,245620,29241602,Posted: 13 January,all,Biscotti187,"I feel bad leaving a negative review, I really do, because a part of me wants to love this game and I burned many hours on Tropico 4. However, I haven't finished the campaign and do not feel the DLC merits spending because of glaring gameplay issues and I really hope the developers read this and there will be a new and improved Tropico 6. The short version is that you will probably be better off buying 4 if this interests or taking a pass if you are only tacitly interested in city simulators. On the off chance that a developer will read this though (or if you are really curious), there is a long version below.I want to start with the positive. The new look of Tropico 5 compared to 4 is an improvement, the basics of running an economy is still there and I appreciate buildings like the office block which rewards you for building a large and dense city just when natural resources will start running out. I feel like if they expand ways for you to make money outside of pulling crops, metals and oil out of the ground then the sequel will give people the freedom to construct much more personalized cities that fit their own styles. I also like that a new level of complexity has been given to elections but that is where we quickly run into problems.The fundemental problem of Tropico 5, which made it too frustrating for me to want to finish, is the dimension that requires you to keep control of island despite elections, coups and revolutions. People who move from Tropico 4 to 5 will be startled what a much larger role factions play in getting re-elected. Now you can largely ignore basic services and as long as you build a new church or start taxing the rich at election time you can make huge gains. Unfortunately, this is very poorly communicated. The most effective thing to do is to see which factions have the largest populations, see which ones you can make happy at the same time and then tailor your constitution and edicts accordingly. However, while you can guess who will like what changes (ten dollars for guessing the Religious will like a Theocratic State) there will often be people who dislike one change that you could not really have forseen and because there is also a penalty in relations from changing policies that people liked you are quickly trying to fix them all before all of a sudden you lose.I get the feeling that the first couple levels were trying to familiarize you with this system but because I was able to beat them without going in-depth, and no text pointed me in the direction of the factions, this was a poor tutorial. I ended up having to look up why I was having so many popularity issues (strictly in the game I mean). A tooltip under edicts, buildings, and amendments that told you who liked what and by how much would have gone a long way. If that is too much handholding it would be fine if there was an option to disable it. However, it would allow one to more effectively build a coalition by avoiding decisions that will permanently and unforeseeably damage relations with one faction. Without being able to be that effecient, I feel like I am constantly trying to patch relations to please these factions so I do not suffer a game over. While some people may like this, I feel that these challenges should force a player to adapt their city, not completely rewrite. The way it is now, I feel that I do not have any substantial control over how I build on the map and then ruins the city builder fantasy for me.Along similar lines, if we had more information on triggered revolts and coups then I feel like this game would be alot less frustrating. I saw other people calling attention to this in the comments and I feel like it would go a long way towards helping. I am not sure if the difficulty itself actually need to be reduced but I definitely feel that I do not have a way to address these fundemental obstacles in the game, lose, eventually get frustrated and just quit. I mostly play it on the offchance of a eureka moment that will finally let me finish the campaign, but I am not holding out much hope. I hope great strides are made in Tropico 6 but I will have to wait a while before I decide to buy it."
