,Recommended,245620,11654976,"Posted: 11 August, 2014",all,Tiefster,"Quick pros and cons of Tropico 5Pros:-Grander scope-You can research techs (as opposed to Modern Times where you had to wait for buildings to unlock)-Constitution is a fun dynamic-Trade routes are a great addition and extra docks are more than just another pick up point for exports-New edicts and edict system (""freebies"" to the people aren't a sure fire way to please the people I've actually had to repeal free food in some cases)-More unique raw resources and industry options-More robust politics and diplomacy-No more ""one economy fits all"" economic strategies-Less ""build building x to make people y happy"" missions-Campaign is greatly improved, you play on two islands that remain unchanged mission to mission-Building upgrades no longer exclusive to industrial and residential buildings-""Repair All"" button after a disaster is a welcomed additionCons:-Learning curve might be a little steep for newcomers compared to older Tropico games-Politics can be muddled at times-Spending money to explore the island is dumb-Invasion combat seems one sided as my defenders have only won twice despite being fairly robust-Building aesthetics through the eras are unchangedOther Thoughts:-Managers system is a little useless in the early game-Dynasty system is interesting but there's no real introduction to it-It's slightly more difficult to gauge what your citizens want so popping up a few churches, clinics, and markets is not a sure way to make your early game citizens happy-I saw a lot of reviews saying most of the humor was taken out of the game which may be true when it comes to building descriptions and the radio broadcasts but the dialogue of your advisers and foreign powers is still pretty funnyIf you're a fan of the Tropico franchise or city builders this game is easy to recommend. However, if you were expecting the same old Tropico you may be little disappointed at first."
