76561198043254294,Recommended,245620,22854216,"Posted: 7 May, 2016",all,The World is a Sandbox,"I'll finally post my review of Tropico 5, sort of as my swan song to my long history with a game I've come back to countless times since it was released back in 2014. Back then I bought at full price, same for the two extensions (Waterborne and Espionage), and many of the DLCs (mostly to get my hands on new maps). I've not regretted a cent of that cumulative purchase price; it's come out to about $1 for 10 hours of pure play time. I spend $3 every day for my morning coffee, and about 6 bucks to throw a dart at a balloon at the county fair to win a pink elephant which I couldn't even convince my girlfriend to carry. If you niggle about a dollar or two more or less for this much value that you get with Tropico 5, there's something wrong with you. If you still haven't purchased it (either you've lived behind the moon or you just took up strategy gaming), it's so cheap now for what you get, just buy it. End of THAT discussion.I'm finally posting a review also to counter the many posts from the good people who love their Tropico 4, and post negative reviews on this board. It's a blessing and a curse for any creative to create something that is so strongly adopted by many. You may have followed the saga of the unfortunate Alden Ehrenreich, who Disney cast to be the young Han Solo in new episodes of the Star Wars franchise. Mr. Ehrenreich will not live another happy day on social media because the die hard, self appointed guardians of the Star Wars fantasy galaxy will rather have a septuagenarian Harrison Ford act out a young Han Solo than - heresy - a young and fairly unknown Mr. Ehrenreich. Something similar seems to be going on with Tropico 4 and now Tropico 5. Tropico 4 created a unique world that sucked people in, and with which they became so familiar that anything that breaks with tradition becomes a bridge too far for some. But to continue a successful franchise means sometimes having to take things into a new direction. Tropico 4 already got cluttered, and its graphics and tool tips and drop down menus betrayed its origin in the age of desktop computers running Win XP Pro with a middling graphics card. At a certain point, the economics of game development are inescapable: you have to be able to address a user base beyond your hard core niche players (who aren't getting any younger either), and open up to new systems (consoles). Firaxis did the jump with going to Civ 5 from Civ 4, and the reactions were similar. In the end, I've logged many, many hours on Civ 5, seen the modders base for that game grow exponentially and churn out awesome free mod products, and wonder with hindsight what the heck all the fuss was about in the first place. Same with Tropico 5. The devs had to break with some traditions, and what we got - and what you should get - is a game with beautiful graphics (don't buy this with a marginal graphics card, you want to run this on max resolution with all effects and all texturization turned on) and wonderful replayability.This is personal, and may not apply to you, but I found a few decisions the devs took unfortunate. For example, they lost me from ever playing their campaign again when they force you - warning: spoiler -  to switch islands right at the start. There's no rational reason, no macguffin brilliant enough to somehow explain that story-wise, so the devs didn't even try. They just send you on another island. That took me completely out of my little world they had me in, and I never touched their campaign again. You may also find that the wit of the base series is lacking from the DLCs, which veer into slapstick and - again for me personally - made them too silly for me to care. I did wholeheartedly adopt Sandbox mode, in which I think Tropico 5 truly shines. Again, it's a special beast: those who wish for a city builder a la the old Sim City franchise before EA inexplicably decided to drive that against the wall, or the more recent Cities:Skyline, will find Tropico 5 odd in some aspects. You have to put up with the silly story lines and some extreme abstraction in some aspects of gameplay. The amount of information available to El Presidente is also somewhat limited (but then, you can always just consult the T5 Wiki). But Tropico 5 has something that makes it addicting: personality. If I build a perfect city in a city builder, fine. Yawn, eventually. But with Tropico 5, I found I can build cities, like real cities. With slums. Traffic jams. Political shenanigans and NIMBYs you just can NOT get along with. And you know what? You won't have to. Just have them come out on the street, then roll over them with your tank. And after the mayham of another revolution put down, sit back in your presidential lawn chair on your presidential lawn with your presidentially strong pina colada in hand, and look from atop high out over your sprawling, smelling, living, breathing, but strangely beautiful city, and take in that gorgeous sunset painting the sky behind all those houses in the most magnificant colors any citybuilder will give you. That's Tropico 5 to me, and that's what made all those hours I played it time well spent."
