,Recommended,245620,10231763,"Posted: 25 May, 2014",all,Sicho84,"Ola El Presidente! The best city builder just got better! Improved graphics, a multiplayer mode, a new ""era"" system and many other new features.But not everything is perfect in Tropico 5.The campaign was a bit short for my taste (took me around 8 hours) and it was pretty easy. (played on Medium Settings) Your mileage may vary!They overhauled many of the mechanics and systems in the game and introduced a new ""era"" system, where you start as a colony of the crown in the early 20th century and then need to fight for your independence to advance to the World War era. After that, it's the Cold War era and then the Modern Times era. Each era unlocks new buildings, new upgrades, new possibilities and new political factions and potential invaders. You also need to research stuff and edicts before being able to use them (reminiscent of one of the ""Extra Missions"" in Tropico 4) This gives Tropico 5 a sense of progression that was absent in the previous entries - which is a good thing.However, I think all these changes in the pacing and the mechanics are one of the reasons, why they played it ""safe"" in the buildings department. While the new gameplay systems offer many new things to Tropico veterans, the buildings are mostly the same as in previous iterations... and there are less buildings as in Tropico 4.The game features all of the usual buildings and infrastructure (houses, roads, Teamster office, factories, military buildings etc.) but it lacks some ""eyecatchers"" and special buildings like the Golden Statue or the Eternal Flame in Tropico 4. Even the tourist buildings are a bit bland compared to the previous games - and there are no more ""tourist attractions"", just hotels/lodgings and some general ""entertainment"" buildings like the Casino or a Restaurant. No more Balloon Rides or Ferry Wheels or Ethnic Enclaves ... the only ""real"" attractions are the new hover gliders and a circus. The rest is - as mentioned - usual ""city"" stuff like the Casino, a Museum, an Opera etc.Other examples of ""absent"" structures: Weather Station, Radio Station (TV and newspaper are still there), Grade School (High scool and College are still there), Radar Dishes ...Also, there are no more foreign army bases, no more Aid Tents, no more Stock Markets or other ""special"" structures with various effects or consequences.Some buildings now have two functions: the Police Station can now be upgraded so that it is also a Fire Brigade. There is no dedicated Fire Bridage building.But this does not mean that you cannot build beautiful and diverse cities in Tropico 5! You absolutely can build great cities! But in my opinion, even with the progressive era system, you will see every available building way to soon... especially since you'll know 95% of them if you played Tropico 3 or 4.The game is however as addicting as the previous entries in the series. The Sandbox Mode will provide me with many more hours of entertainment and achievement hunting. (already played the game for 25 hours at the time of writing this review) They also added a Multiplayer Mode, which is fun but - at the time of writing - very buggy. You can play Versus and Coop and you can set your own winning conditions like ""first one to get 1 Million in Cash"" or ""First one to build a Nuclear Rocket"" etc.Even though this review might sound negative, I absolutely recommend this game! The graphics are great, the gameplay is a lot of fun and addicting, the music is still awesome (I liked some tracks in Tropico 4 better, but that may be a matter of taste) and the humor is still there (even though I find the game to be somewhat less cheerful / over the top than Tropico 4)!I'm looking forward to play many more hours of Tropico 5 in Multiplayer and Sandbox Mode and I'm also looking forward to coming DLC or Add-Ons! There's hope that they will re-introduce some of the ""over the top"" stuff of Tropico 4: Modern Times.Is Tropico 5 a better game than Tropico 4? In many aspects: yes. In some other aspects, it's not. The Tropico series always played it safe and so Tropico 5 is more of an evolution than a revolution. But maybe ""more of the same old"" is actually not that bad. Try to change a formula too much and you end up with a mess. Do I have to mention SimCity here or did you get it right away? ;) (but I have to admit: I like the new SimCity, even with all its problems!)If you played Tropico 3/4: Tropico 5 is a very, very good game but it won't surprise you much, as it is ""more of the same"" with better graphics and a new progression system. Still, it is very good!If you never played a Tropico game (or only the 2D versions): you'll be in for a treat!In this genre, there aren't many competitors that are as good as Tropico 5! So grab your copy now ... or else!!!Viva Tropico!"
