76561198124690229,Recommended,245620,16666782,"Posted: 23 June, 2015",all,FMcCock,dictators
,Not Recommended,245620,10494466,"Posted: 16 June, 2014",all,kingfisherofthesea,"I bought this game after reading ""reviews"" on Steam & other sites touting this as a good, improved successor to the earlier games. My beef with the game is not about the bugs or the fact that content that should have been in the base-game are now locked away in DLC (although these 2 factors certainly contributed to the lack of enjoyment of the game), but the overall regression of the game: Gameplay-wise, Simulation-wise & Humour-wise. This changed from Tropico 4 to Carribean SimCity/Anno/Banished.What made Tropico 4 awesome was the fact that you could follow a single Tropican and really feel as though this is a live person with hopes and dreams and family connections. In Tropico 5, not only can you NOT zoom in all the way to view the Tropican (jobs now share same character models), they don't do any interesting animations even if you decide to stalk them. People no longer stagger out of taverns drunk. And mothers don't get pregnant and stop work - they pop babies out of nowhere. Old people aren't old in the overworld. They don't record a history of past jobs and job experiences gained. Tropicans no longer have individual stats that indicate how stupid/intelligent, courageous/cowardic or leadership/non-leadership material they are. People truly become aggregate statistics. Like resources I could use and dispose without any attachment.Election speeches which gave El Presidente a personal touch and added to the humour of the game, are no longer present. The presidente and your dynasty members just bum around all day doing nothing, their existence justified only by the modifier buffs they have.Even the new features introduced felt extremely gamey.You pop out a dynasty heir due to your ""rrrolicking sex life"" but we are never introduced to the spouse/partner. And you don't get to choose the name of your kid. Come to think of it, I don't think you can rename your Tropicans either.I don't know how trade routes work, but I was under the impression I had to fulfill a contract of shipping a set quantity of resources within a time limit of 5 years. But after shipping my first batch of less than 1000 resources the game decided I fulfilled my requirements and the active trade route disappeared.The humour of the game was truly lost by bad voice-acting and lame jokes. Where is my Brunhilde Van Hoof? El Diablo? Where is my smarmy Penultimo? Instead we get characters that take themselves too seriously like Evita Vasquez, the Crown toad and that Illuminati guy. You also have to suspend your disbelief with bizarre choices like female soldiers and miners in the Colonial Era.The almanac interface was also NOT user-friendly, as there were no back buttons to the previous page. Information was also presented in a clusterf**k of texts.To say this game was a disappointment is an understatement."
