,Not Recommended,245620,10286100,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,Waywocket,"If you enjoyed Tropico 3 or 4 - don't get this. It's a watered-down knock-off.In most respects, this is a simplified version of Tropico 4, with fewer options and less customisation. The few additions, most notably the eras system, don't really add anything to the game except arbitrary limits on development at various stages, effectively capping your happiness and increasing the risk of rebellion.The game has a far higher emphasis on combat then previous Tropicos, both versus rebels and foreign invasions, but it retains the autonomous nature of your army - you can't issue orders, so you get to spend a great deal of time watching your island get overrun while powerless to do anything about it.Tropico 4 had very weak low-budget graphics - just compare it to other games of around the same age like Anno 2070 and it's clear they're not playing in the same league. Tropico 5 adds higher system requirements in exchange for a very marginal improvement: it's still far worse looking than games released several years ago, but a marginal improvement is at least an improvement. In contrast, the music and the voice acting are markedly inferior to Tropico 3 and 4.And then there are the bugs. Like Professional Army actually *reducing* your army's effectiveness, or mission 2 of the campaign not actually loading without a workaround. Put alongside the frustrating and unenjoyable gameplay versus previous game in the series, I somewhat suspect this game hasn't received any playtesting outside of the development team.Pretty much the only good point I can come up with is the humour - there are some good jokes and references in there, very much like the previous games.Overall, this feels like a small low-budget indie release that's inexplicably sold at AAA prices. In a few months when the worst of the bugs are fixed and there's a slew of DLC re-adding features deliberately removed, then it *might* be worth picking up if it goes to 75% off or more. Otherwise: avoid."
