76561198031689943,Not Recommended,245620,10268024,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,OTIS,"Tropico 5 a good game, don't get me wrong.  However, if you try to play the game in sandbox mode you quickly learn that the game is designed to be mission based, like Omerta was, rather than a true sandbox like the previous tropicos.You have 4 stages, the colonial era, the world wars era, the cold war era, and the modern era.  You progress to the next era by fulfilling objectives, even in sandbox mode.  In sandbox mode the game does not even tell you what the objective are, but once  they are fulfilled your ""reward"" is to advance to the next era until you win.If you played the previous Tropicos for the campaigns this game if probably for you, however if you want a true sandbox city builder, Tropcio 4 is a better option.  This Tropico seems to care more about the campaign than the sandbox mode."
,Recommended,245620,10304224,"Posted: 31 May, 2014",all,dande313,"I've been a fan of the series since Tropico 3. Tropico 3 and 4 are roughly similar, with Tropico 4 adding more content. They're wonderful games, and I hightly recommend them. On the other hand, tropico 5 has had a serious overhall. There are some similarities, but the whole feel of the game is very different for me (other reviewers disagree). Here's a quick overview of the differences between Tropico 4 and Tropico 5:-First and foremost, this game is HARD! The previous Tropico's were a piece of cake. You could easily win an election 85% for you 15% against (on average, without trying). In Tropico 5, if the people love you, you're usually riding around 65% for 35% against if they love you. Usually it's more 50%/50%, to a lot less. Electrion fraud is often a necessity, and even then it won't guarentee a victory. With rebel attacks, uprisings, and invasions... there's no ""you get one to two chances before you lose"" deal. If you can't repel them, they'll burn down your palace, and you'll lose the game.-Tropico 5's timeline is more well developed than Tropico 4. Tropico 5 no longer keeps track of the actual year (AD) but rather the Dynasty's time in office. You begin in Colonial times, and progress through WW2, the Cold War, and Modern times. Just like in Tropico 4's expansion ""Modern Times"", buildings and edits become unlocked as you progress through the eras. However, you don't progress through the eras just by letting the time pass. Certain objectives need to be met.-The Blueprints from Tropico 4 are non-existant. Instead it's been replaced by a research system. You need to build a library, hire researchers, etc. You get to choose which research (edits, upgrades, buildings).-The international relations has been completely redone. Other nations/pirates/etc can invade. In tropico 4, an invasion by a world super power means you lose the game. In Tropico 5, your army is pitted against the invader's army. You're also able to establish trade roots between you, and other nations/pirates. This will either increase or decrease your relations with certain parties, as well as offer more or less favorable prices for specific goods.-Building managers are included, which can provide a specific benifit to the building.-Instead of being able to control wages, you invest money into a specific building. This increases wages, job quality, etc.-You have to pay to send out explorers to your island. Without this, you cannot discover new resources, or build beyond your prediscovered area. This is annoying, and I've read many complaints on this. But it's more realistic than Tropico 4.-Building placement has been improved. Farms and ranches work within defined perameters, rather than having patches spring up near the farm wherever is best. Also, it's a lot easier to fit buildings closer together and make the most of your land.-The graphics have been ""updated"". In my opinion, it's a bit of an eyesore compared to Tropico 4. With this graphic update, I've heard of people having issues with the graphics running at all on their machines. My computer is only two years old, and had the latest, top of the line graphics card when I bought it. Never even had a so much as a stutter playing any AAA title, and yet I had to turn down the graphics for this game to run smoothly.There's also one major con I want to point out to those who are not familiar with Kalypso media. There will be between 5 to a dozen DLC ranging between $4-$6 that add minimal content and brush up the game. This is true for almost every game they've published since steam, and they're usually ""patch update"" quality. It's one of the things I dislike most about the company, and it is certainly this way with Tropico 5. You're not paying for the complete game. For that, I'd expect to chip out another $40 over the next few years."
