,Recommended,245620,10221709,"Posted: 24 May, 2014",all,carbonytte,"The overhaul were probably fantastic, but surely not perfect.Cons:DX11 - A lot of people seems to say this, but honestly, I didn't really realized that this was DX11. Graphically this looks the same with Tropico 4.Borderless windowed - There's probably a setting for this but I couldn't find it. By default it loads in ""borderless windowed"" mode rather than fullscreen mode, which means that if you're using multiple monitors display, moving the mouse towards the edge of the game display might make the mouse moves outside the game window already. This, is definitely a No-No for people who uses multiple monitors for their display output.Free-roaming Dynasty Avatar - Unlike having only one character, you create a dynasty which starts with you making a character, and then get more characters in your dynasty through in-game events. That's kinda cool, however in Tropico 4, we can move the avatars to a building which is being constructed just to speed it up. In Tropico 5, the avatars were all free roaming and there seems to be no way to control them.Pro :Tech Tree overhaul - The tech tree looks more complex and compelling compared to Tropico 4, in a good way.Historical Progress - You first start as being a governor to some West India Company (I'd guess it's British, I might have skipped that one in the intro), slowly gain independence and then start to become the head of your own country. After gaining independence, you enter the World War, being stuck between two great powers (Allies and Nazi). Then your progress to Cold War (still only two great powers, you can befriend US or Russia, or both) and lastly Modern Times. This, is quite the fun.Trade options - Rather than waiting for in-game events in order to trade with other nations, you can also use sign a trade agreement with other nations at any time (note : you only sign the agreement, this means that you're not the one proposing to import/export a resource/goods to other nations, but simply open up the trade options and choose what's available at the moment (I think in multiplayer we may be given the option to set some trades with other players, but I haven't try the multiplayer yet)Multiplayer - I haven't try this one yet, but if there's a reason why you want to buy Tropico 5, it's definitely the option of pitting yourself against others.That said, to me the 4rd pro reason is the only reason why I'd say ""Yes, buy this game"". Else, you're better off playing Tropico 4. The rest are kinda cool (historical progress, dynasty avatars) but I just don't really see the difference with Tropico 4. Multiplayer is probably the only reason a Tropico 4 player wants to get his hands on Tropico 5."
76561197986564754,Recommended,245620,10212396,"Posted: 23 May, 2014",all,Afghanicus,"TL;DR Worth the price, much improved, lots of fun!More than a mere update or expansion when compared to Tropico 4; a major leap forward. Micromanagement has been streamlined and cut where necessary to create a very fluid expirience. The campaign has a more homogenous feel and a sense of purpose provided by the characters ""dynasty"" and ""era's"" style of progression.The game so far (5 hours) exhibited a high level of polish that's become uncommon with modern releases. Great fun and humour throughout as would be expected from those familiar with the series. Warfare has been implemented exceptionally well without diminishing the other aspects of the game.If you're on the fence (price wise) play Tropico 4 first and if you enjoy it GET TROPICO 5For those who enjoyed Tropico 1-4 (as I did) what are you waiting for? GET TROPICO 5"
