76561198050481224,Recommended,245620,10405007,"Posted: 9 June, 2014",all,YliTumppi,"Sadly this is another series that loses its idea as it gets diluted down to bland and simplified. Earlier incarnations of tropico were a lot less politically correct, and thus gave much more lols and feels in general. This time that downward trend is taking a huge step, and the specialness of idea is really watered down to just another citybuilder.Also the gameplay itself is really dumbed down, the noble goal seems to be reducing micromanagement, but it actually fails in that by giving away badly functioning building budgets, while taking away esential tools to efficient city-running. (Rent selector anyone?) Almanac, your primary source of information is also infinitely worse than its predecessor.Some design choises like removal of essential buildings (jail?) or lack of missions points really obviously towards truckload of DLC coming up. There are lots of complaints about bugs, and i did experience teamsters jamming and sound glitches.Seems to be that devs are running out of ides, or more likely the businessmen don't let them be used anymore. I guess it is the sad fate of every succesful game. No risks are allowed, everything potentially offensive is removed and for the sake of larger audience, everything is ""simplified"". Result is tasteless, bland and just riding on tales of glorious past.If you get a steam special discount bundle with DLC included, it is worth it. For full price, definitely not. Already tropico 2 was better as game, and part 3 or its full-price expansion 4 is way better as story."
