,Not Recommended,245620,10381551,"Posted: 7 June, 2014",all,NewageDNE,"Before proceeding, let me tell you this, this will be long and I will try to point out why I didn't like Tropico 5 in detail, if you want the resumed version just check it in the end.To start it off, I didn't enjoy Tropico 5 like I did with Tropico 4, really, it is FAR worst than 4, the humor is way more childish, voice actors changed for your loyal Penultimo that sounds nothing like him and honestly makes him far more boring and, worst of all, the story is just... lame. It felt like it was written in a rush, making it simple with a more than disapointing ending.BUT the game isn't compleatly bad, the mechanic is far more challenging and the era things aswell as the multiplayer are both good, which makes the game enjoyable. Sadly the game doesn't explain many of its new concepts, making it confusing and really frustrating, you'll have to dedicate a good while just checking each screen the game has to fully understand how everything in it works.Tropico 5 also adds a limit to your total population, making your growth stop at a rather bad point, max 2000 people, you'll start to feel such effects of a limited population way before too, at around 900. Some structures feel useless too, such as the subway and the garage, both say they'll increase the efficiency of nearby houses, but they don't really change.Speaking of apparently useless structures, many buildings have an awful tooltip, lacking explanation for how it works. During my first plays I made factory ranches, an upgraded version of ranches and then suddenly it stopped producing. I searched, read the tooltip again and again, checked efficiency, everything seemed normal, only after a lot of frustration I checked the forums to find out it required a supply of corn.Some new concepts are also interesting, but really badly planned out, such as the manager for buildings and dynasty members. Both should help you improve your buildings and offer some sort of use, but they really feel useless, it is REALLY had to see a change in a building with managers. Your dynasty members are basicly that too, improved managers and frankly nothing else. You could also see your swiss bank account has a new use, improving your dynasty members, which isn't that hard and after a while you just say ♥♥♥♥ it to the swiss bank account.Speaking of dynasty members, you can customize them and your character, but frankly? Customization is just AWFUL compared to Tropico 4. Meager 4 or 5 suits which you won't EVER see as your characters are really, really small. Remember how you had to use your presidente for all sort of things? Boosting constructions, moving him to make speeches, help improve a building, you actualy cared for the character and tried to keep track of him. In Tropico 5 you make and forget about him, what is the point of following him if he won't do♥♥♥♥♥♥ You can't control him either.Lastly, upgrades are now boring, really boring. In Tropico 4 you could upgrade something and it would change visually, even if it was a small detail it was a change and it was fun! You could see you had improved that building! In Tropico 5 nothing changes, absolutly nothing, I forgot how many times I ♥♥♥♥ed up because I forgot to upgrade a building because I had NO idea what was and what was not upgraded at that point.Resuming: Tropico 5 is not Tropico 4, see it as a different, harder and way more rushed version of it, otherwise you won't get to enjoy it and YOU WILL be frustrated."
