,Recommended,245620,10268325,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Medieval Nerd,"Finally a meaningful update to the series which isn't in forms of additional buildings or edicts. The 'era system' feel like a nice change, and gives the game a political upgrade for each era. Start as a governer, then deal with the Allies & Axis during World Wars, etc.The research system is a nice addition which breathes life into the series. Perhaps it feels a bit light, but it's a change that most people who like the series will surely embrace. Hopefully we'll get more of it down the road.The new Constitution system completements the Edict system quite nicely. Although I've experienced some strange effects from the constitutional options, it does give you power to shape your regime to your linking.The new Trade system allows you to set up contracts with the existing world powers and supplement your income. I was a bit taken aback how people are more keen on exporting than importing, but I still managed to score some really good contracts which greatly increased the value of the trade goods.Although the era system is a nice addition, I was a bit sad to see that if you finished your era faster than intended. The next era warps you to a set start date. So there are gaps in your timeline which would have been nice to simply allow you to progress through eras at your own pace without messing with the date.The family system is interesting, but takes away of the more expansive good/bad trait system of previous games. I was also a bit sad to see that rulers didn't really seem to age, and for some extremely odd reason my first daughter/son's avatar had super wrinkly faces as if they were in their 80's. Made me laugh more than it was annoying.To my fellow micromanagers out there, there is some form of streamlining to parts of the game. You no longer control wages and instead set the budget of a building which will in turn chage the level of income of it's employees. (poor, rich, etc.) I was a bit disapointed in that, since you could have interesting income discrepencies and use it to keep people loyal. Now that bulding effiency is also tied into the budget, you might end up wanting to put everything at max budget just to get the efficiency increase.The new Almenac generally does a good job at giving decent oversight of your island and it's various statistcal information. Wealth, politcal factions, etc. They took a step away from having little people icons and went for a name/value based list. This allows for greater insight with less clicks, but it's a bit less cute. I'll take the better oversight instead.I've never really played scenarios so I can't really comment on that, but the sandbox is quite fun to play with. And the new constitution system can lead to perhaps a greater replay value to try and use the various options which aren't all politically correct. :)If you liked the previous Tropicos but was left feeling like it wasn't ever adding anythign new to the series, well they finally hammered the nail on the head with this one! Spent 13 hours on it the very first weekend I got it, and I see myself trying it out a few more times! Worth it!"
76561198011097599,Recommended,245620,10268374,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Sir Thomas,Tropico 5 really sets itself apart from the rest of the Tropico series. It shows how much the game itself has evolved with many new vital features. It shows you what it is really like to be a dictator (well sorta) and how easy it is to run a country! (well not really)
76561198012746692,Recommended,245620,10269415,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,The Merry Marquis,"Whilst officially a sequal to the Tropico franchise, the game iteslf feels at times more like a reboot with the amount of changes made. Nonetheless, all changes made feel for the better and while the game istself is not without bugs as of launch, it seems to run fine overall.The dynasty system is well implemented and gives an incentive for multiple playthroughs . The fact that your fully upgraded dynasty can be used in multiplayer matches helps add an interesting, even competetive dynamic to things. Though multiplayer itself could use a bit of polish (but, as it is the first time it has been implemented in the franchise, it gets a pass).Military units and buildings have been changed significantly, as have the way battles work. Your military units are no longer simply all the soldiers on your island, but a select number of ""squads"" whose numbers and types are based on the functioning military building on the island. There is also the added feature of changing targets in battle, leading rebels, uprisings, mutinous soldiers, and even invasion forces (which may now be fought off, albiet only with a strong military) to choose muliple, and differing target during an engagement, eventually leading up to an attack on your palace. However, the introduction of tanks and a Tropican air force allow new methods of handling those who are not staisfied with your benevolent rule.The singleplayer game is much more challenging and dynamic than in the past, as well as much longer. The eras not only extend the length of the average sandbox game, but also make it so that at no point can you get too comfortable with dealing with economic and political situations (a problem that made prior games quickly become dull). Each era has its own issues to address, but also new ways to address them (and previous problems). For instance, the colonial period is more or less a race against the clock to declare independence before your gubernatorial mandate expires, while the Cold War will see you plunged into a tug-of-war between the US and USSR, with Tropico serving as the rope.Gone, however, are the humorous election speeches and dozen or so characters that made the humor of the old games stand out. That is not to say that the humor is absent, but don't expect it to not be as omnipresent as in previous titles, as more focus seems to have been put into new mechanics and gameplay, and less on hiring VA's for voicework.Another issue is the lack of customization options as of launch. The new customization screen for your dynasty allows you to alter the outfits and appearance of your up to seven dynasty members, allowing for greater variety and reflection of whatever imposed personalities you dictate (no pun intended), this even includes cusstomizing the color of said outfits, a completely new customization option from previous games. However, as of launch, there appears to be barely (if even) seven outfit choices for male and female characters. This is gratly disappointing compared to previous titles in the series, which allowed for a variety of possibilites in the look and feel of characters.Also of note is that while the graphical style of the game has been altered somewhat from Tropico 3 and 4, do not expect too much improvement. Buildings look to be rendered at about the same quality as before, as do the enviornments and characters. This may be because of the scheduled Xbox 360 launch (they had to keep it within the limits of the console most likely). Though one notable improvement graphically is the inclusion of a grid overlay, which makes city planning much easier and more efficident.All in all, Tropico 5 (or simply ""Tropico,"" according to the title screen) is a new direction for the series, with several new feartures added and refined. Yet all these many changes seem to be for the better overall, alowing for a more dynamic and challenging experience whilst still maintaining the overall humor and atmosphere of previous titles. A bit of polish and refinement is needed, but it will most likely be covered in coming patches. It is disappointing that many options for buildings and customization shall likely be held back for DLC purposes, but thus is the way of our times.I give them game four out of five stars, for its number of (good) changes, but leaving one for the necessity of minor AI fixes and lack of certain promised features (like encountering tribes) and for a significant lack of building types compared to prior titles like Tropico 4 ( a disappointing things for a ""city-builder""). I highly recommend this title for any fans of the Tropico series, and also as a good starting point for those who have yet to play but show interest in the franchise. Overall, a strong entry into this classic series that serves as a breadth of fresh air.Here's to a New Dawn in Tropico!Viva El Presidente!With all respect thusly owed,His Excellency"
