,Recommended,245620,10578230,"Posted: 20 June, 2014",all,Adam T,"Tropico 5: Improved Tropico but Still Too Small?While I am still arguably cutting my teeth on this game, with my previous experience withTropico 3and4I feel relatively competent in reviewingTropico 5at this point. As such, and in a word, this game is animprovementto the franchise.This game takes clear cues from theCivilizationseries while still staying true to theTropicofeel that it has already established. The tech tree is a clear example of this. There are eras within which you must research most of the technologies before you are capable of advancing to the next era. However, again, these have the Tropico flair to them.Another improvement or expansion that I have particularly found enjoyable is the Dynasty feature. This allows you to maintain a set of rulers each which can provide specific boosts to your island. Likewise, each of these can be upgraded through an expanded Swiss Bank system. Ultimately, you can retire Dynasty members which you dislike, and all can be customized in theirstyle. Yes, just their style as, after your first ruler which permits full customization, all subsequent members are ""born"" and you can only make changes that would be realistic in this regard (their hair and clothes basically). While I appreciate that some will certainly dislike this anti-feature, I actually like it.While I have enjoyed these and other aspects of the game, I am also unfortunately already getting a bit bored with it. A slight cure to this has been going back and forth between the Story and the Sandbox modes. The story allows me to play with very specific goals in mind, boost my Swiss Bank, upgrade my Dynasty, and ultimately to learn how to better optimize my islands. In contrast, the sandbox allows me to go nuts with attempting my idealized configuration of island. Similarly, I have started to use the achievements to a similar end. I will also begin to utilize the new co-op feature in this regard as well.Generally speaking this has been my main problem with Tropico 5 (as well as 3 and 4), as for whatever reason, I just do not find the game to be highly replayable and indeed find it fairly repetitive after I get the basic setups figured out. In essentially every other way I find the game to be fun and well done. It just fails to hook me for extended periods of time (though I have the same problem withCivilization, andDemocracy: I always wantmore!).With that said, whileTropico 5has generally expanded on much offered inTropico 4, including essentially all the DLC expansions that Tropico 4 eventually had (Firaxis could learn from this) there are parts that feel short-changed and that I strongly suspect will ultimately be fleshed out withTropico 5sown subsequent DLC. (While specific examples are escaping me at the moment I will edit and update this when I next notice one.) This is not an inherently negative aspect to this game, but as I indicated above in my quest for extensive customization in these types of games, this is something that stands out to me.With all that said, I stillstrongly recommendthis game for those that like this genre. Though, perhaps wait for a good sale and some DLC before hopping on board!"
