76561198079377033,Recommended,245620,22534745,"Posted: 20 April, 2016",all,Wasted Youth,"Although I enjoyed Tropico 4, I was almost discouraged from buying this game by some of the negative reviews. I'm glad that a combination of boredom and curiosity eventually got the better of me, because in most respects, I found Tropico 5 to be even better than its predecessor. This review will cover the Complete Collection, and is aimed at those who have played previous versions and are wondering how this one measures up. If you've never played a Tropico game before and you like city builders, stop reading now and just buy it. It's addictive, has great replay value and is at times hilarious.The campaign in 5 is vastly superior compared to 4. The story is better and it's more fun to play. In 4, I found it really annoying that you had to start over on a new island for each level of the campaign. Just when I'd got a map to the point where I really liked it, I'd win the campaign and have to start from scratch again. In 5, this is not the case. You alterate between two maps throughout the campaign (although the number of maps increases as you progress to the later levels) and your progress from the previous level is saved. So when you start a new level, you'll get the map you previously worked on, exactly as you left it. Sometimes you'll get a choice of which of your previous maps you want to play on. In some of the tougher parts of the campaign, your choice of map can make the difference between winning and losing.Which brings me to another point in 5's favour (at least for me): The campaign is more challenging than it was in 4. Even on medium difficulty, I had to replay certain chapters several times and really think about my strategy in order to beat them.Instead of playing with one dictator and levelling up various traits, you'll now be able to switch between dynasty members who each offer different types of bonuses for your settlement. At certain points in the campaign you'll be offered the opportunity to add new members to your dynasty. You can customise the appearance of dynasty members and level them up by spending money from their Swiss bank accounts. You can also switch between them by deciding which family member is going to stand for election.In my opinion, the DLC is much better implemented in 5 than it was in 4. For example, it's no longer a no-brainer to upgrade apartment blocks to modern apartments. I found that I needed some of each in order to get the balance right between housing satisfaction and what my people could actually afford. There are also some great new buildings; I never knew how much I needed a drone command center to annihilate criminals or ""accidentally"" take out citizens with low opinions of their benevolent ruler.Finally, I'll briefly address some aspects of 5 that other reviewers have cited as negatives: Yes, it costs money to uncover foggy parts of the map ($1000 per exploration mission, to be exact). However, you can send a search party to just about anywhere on the island. Also, the map is automatically completely revealed after a few chapters, irrespective of where you have explored in the past. You can vastly reduce the expense of exploration by making strategic decisions about where to send your party.It is true that you can't control your troops in combat, and I'll concede that my so-called professional soldiers made some tactical decisions so stupid that I doubted they had completed grade school, let alone high school. Instead of grouping up then ambushing the enemy, lone squads insisted on trickling off and tackling squads four times their size. You can ameliorate this issue somewhat by grouping your military structures together and around buildings that the enemy is likely to target, but the fact that your army is seemingly comprised of complete idiots does get frustrating at times.TL:DR - if you liked 4, get 5. It's more difficult than its predecessor, but once you get the hang of the nuances that have been introduced in this version, it's a lot more fun."
,Recommended,245620,22573751,"Posted: 22 April, 2016",all,tdk5001,"The Tropico series has been great and although the game keeps its character, it evolves with every series in different directions - which is something the developers can and should be proud of.I do like the history timeline that was added to this latest edition and I think some of the mechanics in terms of transportation have been improved!What I would like to see in the next edition is:- return to more micromanagement of the people. I do think that the managers' system that was introduced in this edition is a very good idea but yet I would like to see more individuality in this and almost would like to be able to employ the closest and best managers to work for me from when I find them until they die.. (pretty much)- I would like to see more competition from the different faction leaders and more individuality to those throughout the game as part of the resistence, maybe introducing parades, protests etc. against ""the regime"" so that they feel like real competitive individuals and not just random computer generated people who run against you in elections..- I would like to see more customisation of your own character and your managers (based on the idea above) and maybe potentially your main opponents (my second point above).. that would further enhance the individuality and the presence of real opponents.- I would like to see more technology, more choice of buildings of the same type, maybe even be able to somehow affect the cars/transportation your people are using.. (obviously all of that can and probably should be done in following DLCs)- I think the dynasty idea in this edition has been handled very well and the fact that you can have a number of dynasty members is a great introduction, but I would like to see more traits, more character and, again, individuality in each member.. almost on the principles of traits in Total War series.. or maybe even Sims..- I think the economy in this edition has been handled amazingly well but I would like to have more control on the import / export and production / consumption of goods. This has been addressed to an extent in this game but I think it would be cool if, for instance, when people only have one type of food - they protest... or for instance you can do edicts which are related to all products in trade and consumption.. the whole geopolitics and trade has to be developed further and resources have to be made renewable or inexhaustible (mainly mines)..Anyway.. that's just a few ideas off the top of my mind.. and I realize they are very onerous and time/budjet consuming ideas probably.. but I do think that this is the direction that this game has to be evolving into. Nevertheless, amazing work by all and everyone who has been part of this project! The graphics, the gameplay, the character of the game, the sound effects, music, voices, the mechanics of the game... great great job!"
