76561198122632662,Not Recommended,245620,19934168,"Posted: 25 December, 2015",all,Rostan,"Note: I changed my recommendation to negative, due to the lack of continued support for this game. It is overall a good game, but bugs and simple flavour-killing lack of diversity are not being addressed at all by the developers, who instead came up with far less useful DLCs adding e.g. military buildings to the already overblown diversity, etc. My initial review for this game was positive, though the lack of further development and eveb basic support made me change my mind.Anyway, the plus for the game:The game is still quite amazing in terms of how it feels. True, like many of the posters have noted, it lacks some features present in Tropico 4. However, it also has numerous improvements.Among the pros, I would like to note:- Nice graphics (especially the nature).- Funny (albeit fewer) radio comments and funny edict and challenge commentaries.- Basic but enriching research compontent.- Much better military component.- One can now keep older buildings and build them in later eras. No longer will a hurricane force you to reconstruct everything a la Hong Kong like in Tropico 4 MT. I love this part as it makes the cities look much more organic, with historic cores, CBDs and 1970´s stile social housing coexisting in harmony.- Improved economic system and high diversity of industrial supply lines.- Upgraded diplomacy.- The population limit is rather adequate.- I think the political system is better, icluding tought competitive elections with faction leaders (rather than 17 year old farmer girls).- Better optimization as compared to T4.Among the cons, of which there are numerous as opposed to T4:- Some useful buildings no longer present (tourism attractions are now all but a skeleton). Ditto for some interesting edicts.- Rudimentary tourism component. I cannot stress this enough. All tourists have just 1 male and 1 female skin, and buildings and attractions have been dumbed down to ""barely existing"".- Colonial epoch very basic, albeit a useful learning tool early on.- Information cumbersome and poor. Tropico 4 almanach was much better. The one in Tropico 5 is broken and the developers have never bothered to fix it, focusing on wacky DLC instead. Also, one can no longer use overlays like housing occupancy, which is a shame.- Lack of ability to zoom up to street level, without mods.- Building and person skins are reduced to a bare, unrealistic, simplified minimum. Gone are the super-diverse, gritty yet detailed looks of Tropico 4, replaced with some generic undiversified construction patterns.- The DLC policy is weird, and most DLC buildings are extremely odd (and in my opinion poor choices). You will still not get a chance to build separate police and firemen buildings, or to have 2 different skins for tenements, but you have 4 types of floating buildings and 12 types of military random edifices. These game design choices are difficult to understand for me.Overall, still a very good game. After buying it, I said I will not return to Tropico 4 any time soon, despite missing certain features. In the end, I did, as the lack of support and weird design choices have robbed Tropico 5 of its full potential, and have made it go - IMHO - along the Kalypso path of increasingly sub-par games."
