,Recommended,245620,20328508,"Posted: 5 January, 2016",all,Foxysen,"Tropico 5 is yet another sequel to Tropico, a series of city-building games as dictator of Banana Republic. This one was released in 2014 by Haemimont Games. At least they waited 3 years since Tropico 4. Now with multiplayer!It also came out for Xbox 360 and PS4. Xbox One version is planned. Don't know of any good difference. So relax and enjoy PC version.Technically there was a huge slashback because the game requires videocards that support DirectX 11 and nobody ever reads System Requirements. Or maybe it wasn't written at launch, I didn't check back then. Also, some complaints about bugs, but most of it probably got fixed by now.Multiplayer community seems to be here. It employes chat-room and I can see a dozen of players here, with messages popping up that somebody is making a new game. So it may take 5-10 minutes to get game running, but at least it's not empty. Most often you see games of World War era with tons of starting money and no victory requirements, I guess that people here favour deathmatch type of games.So, Tropico 5.Main plot of this part is that Penultimo grew a moustache.Unlike Tropico 4 which barely added anything to Tropico 3, Tropico 5 changed few things up. I don't know about others, but I am thankful that I don't have to do more of same tactics and that it became a bit more challenging in mechanics too.I mean, from one point some may think that game got dumbened down. For example, you set one of 5 pre-defined budget on each building unlike previous Tropico games where you could set any wages you wanted to each building. But where Tropico 1 was so difficult that you had to care about such thing, in Tropico 3 and 4 it mattered little, as in those games you just slammed production and then Industry building onto island and would go on fiesta as money rained on your head, once in few years increasing wages for everybody by one to keep them happy. At least Tropico 5 budget increases effectiveness as well, like Teamsters can carry more.Yea, it's not Tropico 1. But at least they refocused around to make it more interesting, less fluff. Or at least different. Because after playing Tropico 3 and 4 I am happy with some core difference.You now can advance through the four eras. To reach each new era you usually have to research all era's stuff and then do little quest of sorts. I actually love strategies where you can advance through era, combining both historical interest along with seeing all your units and buildings getting upgraded (Where is Empire Earth on Steam, Rebellion?!). Not so much here, being too tongue-in-cheek for historical and not updating looks of everything as often. But hey, still something.- Colonial era. Allows only extraction of island's raw resource. Out of industry there is only Lumber Mill, which is like a middle between Woodcutting and Furniture anyway. Out of foreign powers there is only The Crown and it's pretty linear, as you have to increase revolution supporters on island, mostly by side quests. Also, no healthcare at all. Watch Royalists die. No elections, but your time on governer's seat is limited and you have to do The Crown missions to increase them. Interesting, but linear.- World War era. Now with two foreign powers and more classical Tropico gameplay with elections. You now get access to industry to finally make tons of money. Just make sure to have a good standing with both factions when advancing to next era.- Cold War era. You now have access to tourism. I actually didn't figure out how to make tourism effective, I still would focus on production as always. I did notice that Tourism houses are quite expensive, hm. It probably isn't so nice that it gets introduced this late.- Modern Times era. Now a whole bunch of foreign powers, but only US can invade you. Have access to everything. Not much else to say.Another awesome thing is trade system. In Tropico 4, which introduced it, I remember it being as something automatic and then I stopped caring. Here you have limited ships which can carry limited amount of recources per once and you have to set each ship to any trade routes that you got. You may find out that the only industry export is for steel for 10 years, so you can choose to build Steel factory. And then find out that your Iron mines ran out and you now have to import some iron. It's quite good addition.Then comes a whole bunch of small differences. Like, budget instead of wages. Or you can set a manager for each building for additional bonuses, reminding me of Tropico 2. Hm, actually some music track reminds me of that part too, that game was focused on Pirate theme.You also have improved battles handling. You can't control them, but battles now look like battles and offense will try to destroy some of infastructure, quickly moving between then, until getting to the palace. While defence still rushes dumbly all over the map from the base. Build watch towers to slow down offence, yep.Or the wacky way that buildings are being built. Seems like the construction workers have to touch it once for it to slowly get 17% or so built automatically by itself for next few seconds. But I had little issue with constructions in this game, so it must work better with this AI.Or you have now a whole dynasty of El Presidente on a map. But in this game you can't control them at all, only set some as managers. So they are just there hanging around for bonuses. And hey, you got use for Swiss bank now as you get to upgrade family.Actually, you can't do some micromanaging things of dictatorship now. Like, no golden statue to waste money on. Or you can't move your presidente to attack rebels or speed up construction. Or you can't easily win votes by promising things. Though no complaints as it brings some challenge back, selling bonds to get money to do something fancy to impress people with.Heck, people even say that it doesn't even have a prison to arrest people into.Even though I remember that I could build some prisons in Cold War era. Wait.Ohhhh, they updated game since then: putting save feature into multiplayer, implenting Steam Workshop and putting a prison building for free. Nice. You would think that they would make it part of their tiny DLCes.Oh, and there is campaign. It's quite nice. Humor. The Order. You now have few island and game will make sure that you will revisit all of them, having to do stuff on top of your early mistakes.Sadly, announcers and music is a bit less awesome. Especially radio announcer, who is some girl who keeps inviting men to Jolly Roger for fun times. And punishes players for building lumber mill by proving the world that she can do the most annoying sound ever. At least each tiny DLC now promises a new music track.Well, and multiplayer. You can play it competevily and cooperatively. It's still works as good as you can imagine such city-building to be. Mostly that army rushing isn't all that fitting to game's pace and that players don't really interact much otherwise. But hey, at least some of random objective are challenging, like getting 100000 of team money. Can share recources and connect roads with same team too.Oh well, I can see it being really nice with friends.Tropico 5 is interesting part, trying to reform some parts of gameplay and I like some of the stuff that it does. It's a bit more challenging than Tropico 4, but it doesn't have as much of Dictatorship funzies. As for me, I am happy that it's not more of same like T4."
