76561198024806132,Recommended,245620,10643929,"Posted: 21 June, 2014",all,Silver22,"What the Tropico series seems to understand better than some other strategy games is that quality trumps quantity when it comes to strategic options.Especially in the earlier eras, you will find fewer choices in Tropico 5 than in Tropico 4.  Early ages especially have few buildings in each type. Building management options is based on a budget (affects service quality and wage at the same time).  In general, specific numbers are replaced with broad categories (see budget).However, these are all good things.  Ultimately, entry fees, rents and wages were largely either trial and error, following a guide or broad categories anyways in Tropico 4.  Tropico 5 doesnt offer a lot of options all the time, but each is distinct in at least some ways, and not to be taken lightly (especially constitution principles, which are logically harder to change than small picture policies).Overall, the eras system gives the game good pacing, the new algorithim provides challenge to more experiences players, and Tropico's humor is still alive and well.  You could do a lot worse."
