,Not Recommended,245620,11421706,"Posted: 26 July, 2014",all,Billy Snuggles,"Thesis: A Dissappointing sequel, suffering from all the problems of the current generation.The graphics are very nice. I'd go so far as to say they're gorgeous. And Tropico 5 now has a clear reason to build multiple docks: the trade route system. Now, if you want to, you can find a trade route to export or import certain materials for better prices than base. However, there is still a base cost. This system hits that ideal balance: for players that want that extra granularity, it's there. But if you don't want it, don't bother.Those are all the nice things I can say about this game. Tropico 5 has less than half the content of Tropico 4, in terms of options, buildings, and characters. I'm not including any of the DLC in that statement. I mean, base game to base game, half the content. Further, most of the content is Unlockable. That would be fine, except their decisions are baffling and frustrating.I personally enjoy building Tourist economies. Tropico 5 doesn't unlock any tourism until the Third phase of the game, Cold War. This doesn't make sense. There was plenty of Tourism in the Colonial age, and Nazis and Allies had down-time in between all the fighting. We had the potentail to make Casablanca, and Kalypso denied us! By the time the Cold War comes along, it no longer makes sense to build Tourism, because your Industry will be well established.The touted Eras mechanic is choppy and shallow. There's no fluidity, like in Modern Times. It's an abrupt Scene-change that CANCELS ALL YOUR ACTIVE TRADE ROUTES. And there's not much to it except the names of the people you trade with and who might invade you change. Seriously. Even in the Story Mode, the different Eras mean almost nothing.And the Dynasty system might as well not be there. Instead of choosing a variety of skills for your Presidente, you pick one. And then you randomly get heirs who RANDOMLY get one skill. You can then choose which member of the Dynasty to run in an Election. That's it. Hooray. But your main Presidente is apparently Ra's a Ghul, because they don't die of old age, so you can have the same Presidente for close to 100 years.The biggest issue is the lack of character. None of the missions have the same feel as in Tropico 4. I just didn't get invested in it. None of the different characters show up, except Penultimo, but he's got a giant moustache and a new voice actor. No naive Sunny Flowes, no sultry Miss Pineapple, no greedy Antonio Lopez, no drunken Father Esteban. There's some new characters, but Kalypso cut down on those as well, so you have characters pulling double- or triple-duty on representing the different factions of Tropico.  We don't even get special, Era-specific characters. The Foreign representative is the same dude from Colonial Times. No Nazi weasel or Imperial Japanese bureaucrat contact you with enticing demands. Just Lord British of Englandshire, who then relays the message to you of Axis offers.To summarize, Tropico 5 offers insultingly little content for a brand new game. If you're coming into the Tropico Franchise brand-new, buy Tropico 4 with all the DLC and expansions. If you already own Tropico 4 with all the DLC and expansions and have played them to death, keep playing them.As a final note: There is the possibility that Kalypso will release an expansion that makes me change my mind. I only played Tropico 4 once all the way through before Modern Times addicted me. It so thouroughly changed the game in my mind that I have replayed the entire game, even the base, multiple times.So if they release an expansion pack that adds depth to the Eras or characters or maybe even a Tourist Heaven, with eight new missions and twelve new buildings that allows Tourism throughout the whole game, I promise to change this review.That said, their first DLC out of the gate is a building for cheese making."
