76561198027626890,Recommended,245620,11413398,"Posted: 25 July, 2014",all,Joe Momma,"Tropico 5 is not a disappointment, but it isn't a smash hit either.There are some notable improvements. I love the building grid, it allows me to quickly and accurately place everything without obsessing about being off by a few inches. I love the new graphic elements (the ones that weren't recycled from previous iterations). I enjoy the ""modernize"" feature - no need to bulldoze your tenements if you want to move on to apartments, and to modern apartments later.Then there are things that I hate. Castrated Presidente customization screen. The fact that the Presidente and his family are uncontrollable drones just like the rest of the public - I can't go visit my favorite factory or my favorite base or whatnot when I want to, or go resolve a protest by visiting it. Army bases and barracks don't provide living space for the soldiers anymore. Budget system is stupid as hell and can cause you to accidentally crash a thriving economy in the matter of minutes. Teamsters are dumber than ever, and traffic problems are the worst I've seen yet - once you get to World Wars era and beyond, you are presented with a choice of not having enough teamsters to move things around and having your roads gridlocked because cars refuse to take alternate routes.Be prepared to run out of resources and never get them back. That coal mine? It's going to be emptied out by the time you hit Cold War. That oil well? It might last you a bit into modern times, then it's gone baby gone. Want to build a nuclear power station? Be prepared to see it gobble up uranium like it was coal. Once you hit Modern Times,  your long-term income options are: farming, cigars, wood, furniture, chocolate, rum, textiles and clothes, and pharmaceuticals which the pharma company produces from thin air. Imports are broken, so it's almost impossible to produce cars, electronics or jewelry long-term. You could also buy low/sell high, but that puts you at the mercy of random number generator. This seems like a lot of things, but once you get big and need a lot of power stations and apartments to house people, your economy gets positively voracious. I've seen my balance go from positive six digits to negative six digits in matter of minutes.And to top it off, we have the good old issues such as: road placement, non-square corners that you can't fill with anything, tropicans that refuse to take public transportation to drive to work and for some reason build shacks in front of unoccupied buildings... not game breaking, but annoying as all get out.A lot of these issues are solved with mods somewhat, so I recommend you give those a long hard look.Overall I recommend the game - I had a great time playing it - but be prepared to be a little or a lot frustrated with simple stuff that should have been solved in previous iterations of the game. Oh, and all this extra content you are used to from Tropico 4 (statues, gardens, ploppable trees) - gone baby gone. Get ready to pay for more DLC."
