,Recommended,245620,15245507,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,NordicAryan,"I will recommend this game despite it's shortcomings.TL;DRFrustrated with Tropico 4's poor economy design? Find yourself at home here. More of an economy simulator rather than a political simulator. Llarge portion of the political aspect cut or dumbed down, economical aspect expanded upon. Lots of DLC. The graphics are a large improvement over Tropico 4, A step forward in some directions and a step back in others.A few gripes I have about the game:- Your island will most of the time look like a Soviet Era industrial city due to the lack of building variety, as all buildings of the same type have no little to no variation between them, forcing you to have row upon row of identical houses and factories. The strict grid system contributes to this fact.- While Tropico 4 had a large pool of representatives for all factions/countries, this game basically only has 3. That's two people representing half the factions each, and one person representing all the foreign countries. I really miss the variety of characters, as it all added to the political satire as they were mostly based on real life people.- Rebels will appear regardless of approval rating (Highest I've gotten is 98% but still faced constant guerilla attacks on my distant mines and farms)-  DLC!!! As of now there is nearly $50 worth of DLC for a game thats $40. I know Kalypso is money hungry but this is ridiculous.- Penultimo's new voice :(I enjoy particularily:- Traffic jams can finally be avoided by proper planning and management. Teamsters also have a huge improvement- It is a lot harder to win elections and this actually now requires effort- Combat has been hugely improved- Multiplayer is a huge plus, I love co-op games!- The budget system vs salary system removes a lot of micromanagement, although I wish that constitution options would give you a choice of which to use (Free market = Budget, Planned Economy = salary).- In the campaign mode you use the same two islands (alternate between missions) throughout the campaign, meaning it does not reset your island after each mission like in Tropico 4. Encourages long-term planningThere are a lot more minor things I enjoy, and a lot more minor things that annoy me.Overall it's still a fun game, although it does make me go back to Tropico 4 every now and then."
