,Not Recommended,245620,15194578,"Posted: 3 April, 2015",all,mil45 | BuggyRider,+improved graphics-%1 game %99 dlc-%1 game %99 dlc-%1 game %99 dlc-%1 game %99 dlc-%1 game %99 dlc-%1 game %99 dlc
76561198037329627,Recommended,245620,21299742,"Posted: 18 February, 2016",all,Londo Mollari,"One of the most difficult tropico games, given you choose the right settings or workshop scenarios. Lots of fun but if you are easily frustrated play at lowest settings. Some of the dlc is not worth the price but some is. The reviews are pretty accurate and will let you pick which dlc you want. Tropico 5 expands on many areas other Tropico games have not delved into while getting rid of some of the old features (some which were pretty good). As a Tropico game goes this is without a doubt the most unique. In a good way or a bad way is up to the taste of the gamer in question.1. Economy.The economy is much better and more realistic. There are now features like trade routes, which when used effectively can help a lot. Used without the foreign relations penalties in mind can now result in foreign invasions, and trade route embargos. The settings for sandbox maps are more generic in presentation but work just about as well as other Tropico games. Some building upgrades tend to work a bit differently than Tropico 4. I am sorry that i do not know how to adequately describe the changes, yet i find them welcome. If you like the challenge of making money you will enjoy this.There are also buliding managers that provide various bonuses and in some cases both bonuses and penalties to your buildings and even perhaps surrounding buildings. This means citizens now have roles. Some are good roles like supervisor. Some are bad like rebel or with the espionage expansion foreign spy.2. Military.The military game of Tropico 5 has new features. Not only do your troops fight the rebels but ANYONE who attacks your island or your rule. There is still the potential for coups, although personally i find it easier to maintain the military factions' approval than previous Tropico's, but this does not mean the military portion of the game is easier. In fact even on the easiest settings it is more challenging than many other Tropico games. Something else that should be mentioned is there are a lot of military options even in vanilla Tropico 5. If you add dlc and the Espionage expansion you get even more. I think the military game is more realistic as well. YOu can also see the stats of you troops which now operate in squads. There are three stats, attack power, health and number of units in the squad. Troops also do not surrender as easily. Sometimes they will not surrender at all choosing to fight to the last man which i think occurs more often with high miltary loyalty.3. Foreign Relations.This has been changed quite a bit as well. In the colonial era it is really hard to get invaded by the crown. Pirates can invade but are usually easily beaten. I think this is a good balance choice by Kalypso. Nothing is worse in a strategic game than jumping in and being outnumbered and outgunned from the very start, with no chance of preperation. However if you do not prepare for the next eras being invaded by superpowers is much more risky. In the colonial era, the main effect with having bad relations with the crown is lack of trade routes, which can hurt your income and lack of yearly funds sent from the crown, which is not vital but every little bit helps. Latter foreign relations get more tricky to manage, especially in the modern era. Much like Tropico 4 there are 5 factions. Only two can invade you that i know of. The dynamics of trade routes become much more complicated, although Tropico 5 gives you various ways around that, if you invest wisely. You can now import trade goods directly from foreign powers as well as minor powers, smugglers and in the colonial era pirates. With the waterborne expansion smugglers become a more viable option with the smugglers docks building. The Espionage expansion makes significant changes to foreign relations. You now have spies and more ways to detect the roles of citizens. Police stations now help detect the roles of citizens. As a sidenote police stations can now serve the additonal role of fire station with an upgrade. Spies can be used for various missions some of which i am still familiarizing myself with. The ones i am familiar with are steal money and steal technology. That's right Tropico 5 now has research and scientists. Frankly there's not enough of that. It is very reminiscent of a certain mission in Tropico 4 with the exception of the scientists producing the research points. Yet i digress. Nations will now demand more from you including more frequent survival from foreign invasions missions. Most of which occurs in the World Wars era. Embassies are much more functional than the foreign minitry building and provide more options for manging foreign relations. There is a cost for every foreign action, so in actuality foreign relations is harder in my opinion.Island Factions.Throughout most of Tropico 5 i find the importance of island factions is not nearly as important. Actually with the exception of the military faction I ignore the others. Yet this is because the constitution you develop on your island influences them a lot. With the right options island factions can be a dominant force, or firmly under your control which is how i play. If you give a lot of power to the factions on your island i can imagine those factions being more important than in previous tropico games. Factions can now influnce protests.... well as far as i can tell. There are both faction protests and citizen protests.... as far as i can tell. Citizen protests you can buy off, negotiate to do certain tasks to appease them, or send in the troops. Yet this is all fuzzy to me because i never have protests the way i play. I may have a island wide uprising on occasion which my troops will usually put down, but never protests :). Also with the right constitution option it is now possible by all appearances that some military faction supporters can now fight as militia, which is handy during foreign invasions and those nasty island wide uprisings :). It is very possible to have an army of 200 without much effort by the end of the game. One other thing is edicts now can more directly affect miltary strength. Those militia from the milittary faction work almost as well as modern infantry when used with the right to arms edict. Problem is rebels are stronger and those citizens who join the uprisings. Anyone who invades your island and faces 5 squads of modern infantry, 3 tanks squads, 2 apc squads, fighter bombers and cruise missiles ( which is usally what i run with in the modern era, will be promptly, efficiently and quickly squashed with a minimum of effort and collateral damage. Watch out for those fighter bombers they can kill your citizens.In summary Tropico 5 offers many ways to play. In fact more ways than previous incarnations with the addition of multiplayer and workshop content. I give the economic aspect a 9/10. The military aspect a 10/10, the Foreign relations aspect a 10/10, and the Island Factions aspect a 7/10."
