76561198001601065,Recommended,245620,16964423,"Posted: 9 July, 2015",all,Fenylal,"It's surprising how research and progressing through eras makes this game feel fresh and new. There's more to do now, more to fight for, but it's also become a little bit easier in my opinion. However the series seems to have lost much of the personalities of the citizens, I rarely find the need to micro-manage citizens, and issuing edicts on them hardly seems worthwhile. They're just numbers in Tropico 5. Also, the music is more akin to the original Tropico, which is a little calmer and suits well the with colonial era.Surprisingly, the campaign involves only two islands at first! You go back and forth between these islands as the campaign progresses, keeping progress between missions. Then, after the first chapter is complete, you get two new islands to play on, but these are somewhat more difficult. The ending was a bit abrupt, but all in all a satisfactory and somewhat challenging campaign.The game has no official support for mods (the devs find it too troublesome to offer support on mod issues), but they still allow mods in the game. I suggest having a look at them, as there are some additions which the devs should have though of from the beginning. Also, the new multiplayer feature seems interesting, though I haven't tried it yet.On the minus side, the game is quite lacking in buildings compared to the previous Tropico. Some people seem to think this is so they can earn more money on over-priced DLC (which I tend to agree, far too expensive for something that's little more than a fan mod), but the game is still enjoyable without the DLC.If you like the Tropico series, this game won't let down. It's more of the same, with some imho great new flavours."
